description.plain:
Willie Junior Maxwell II (b. June 7, 1991), better known by his stage name Fetty Wap, is a rapper and singer coming out of Paterson, New Jersey. He describes his musical style as “ignorant R&B.”

“Fetty” means money and “Wap” is a homage to “Guwop,” a nickname for Gucci Mane (though “Guwop” can also mean money).

Fetty’s known for his breakout hit “Trap Queen” and other songs like “679,” “My Way,” “Again,” and “Jimmy Choo.”

He released his debut eponymous album Fetty Wap on September 25, 2015.

songs.full_title: Trap Queen by Fetty Wap
songs.title: Trap Queen

description.plain:
“Trap Queen” is the gratifying tale of Fetty Wap and his girl teaming up in the drug game. (A “trap” is a place where drug deals happen.) A few months after releasing this song, the Paterson, New Jersey native signed to Lyor Cohen’s 300 Entertainment.

Nearly a year after it was released, the song became a crossover sensation, hitting the #2 spot on the Billboard Hot 100 chart.

Fetty spoke to Complex about his inspiration for the song:

I was just dealing with somebody at the time, and she was holding me down. We were building a lot, and I came up with the concept. She was my trap queen.

The term “trap queen” first appears in Gucci Mane’s 2006 song “Trap Gurl”.

Fetty told Maxim the “song doesn’t have anything to do with love, really…” It’s about a girl who “learned how to cook crack, and she kind of did it so good that she made enough for the both of us,” he says. “She knew how to stretch that shit.”

“It’s not like, ‘Oh, babe, I love you, let’s work for this,’… No, we’re about to go break the law, and we’re gonna have some fun.”

songs.full_title: 679 by Fetty Wap (Ft. Monty, P-Dice & Remy Boyz)

description.plain:
“679” is a party anthem by Fetty Wap and his Remy Boyz crew that Fetty calls a “turn up song.”

The song was originally released on Fetty Wap’s SoundCloud in early 2014, but didn’t blow up until it was re-released with a music video on WorldStarHipHop in May 2015. For Fetty’s album, P. Dice’s verse was replaced by another Fetty verse.

Fetty took to Twitter to explain that the title of the song comes from his birthday, June 7, 1991.

https://twitter.com/fettywap/status/530483727189950465







Produced by long-time collaborator Peoples, the beat was initially intended for Coke Boy rapper Velous who was looking for a Ty Dollar $ign type of feel. Since his team wasn’t really feeling it, Peoples began adding drums and  that’s when Fetty jumped on the track with Monty. The two were finished in an hour.

This verse was first heard on The Black Papi’s Instagram.
